I have now addressed this issue, by taking the approach that it is in the grids module we should have functions which evaluate a function for a given grid. e.g.:

```
class Grid(object):

    def __init__(self, grid):
        self.grid = grid


class GridRegular(Grid):

    def __init__(self, grid):
        super(GridRegular, self).__init__(grid)

    def intensities_via_grid(self, galaxies):
        """Compute the intensity in each pixel using the coordinates of the regular grid"""
        return sum(map(lambda galaxy : self.evaluate_func_on_grid(func=galaxy.intensity_at_coordinates,
                                                                  output_shape=self.grid.shape[0]), galaxies))
```

This nicely ties the grids and function evaluations together. it might not be the best way to handle this, but I'll let you decide if we need a refactor :).

