Hi!

Yes this is possible. You would have to add the configuration to the xAxes scales property.

```python

class BarChart(Chart):
    chart_type = 'bar'
    scales = {
        'xAxes': [{
               'barPercentage': 0.3
        }]
    }

    def get_labels(self, **kwargs):
        return ["January", "February", "March", "April",
                "May", "June", "July"]

    def get_datasets(self, **kwargs):
        data = [10, 15, 29, 30, 5, 10, 22]
        colors = [
            rgba(255, 99, 132, 0.2),
            rgba(54, 162, 235, 0.2),
            rgba(255, 206, 86, 0.2),
            rgba(75, 192, 192, 0.2),
            rgba(153, 102, 255, 0.2),
            rgba(255, 159, 64, 0.2)
        ]

        return [DataSet(label='Bar Chart',
                        data=data,
                        borderWidth=1,
                        backgroundColor=colors,
                        borderColor=colors)]


```

Unfortunately I found out that the convenience method `Axes` used in the examples does not support this property. I will release a new version with support for this property (and some others). Than you will also be able to configure it like this:

```python

class BarChart(Chart):
    chart_type = 'bar'
    scales = {
        'xAxes': [Axes(barPercentage=0.3)]
    }
    # ....

```

In continuous of this idea: 
```python
from marshmallow_peewee import ModelSchema as _ModelSchema
from marshmallow import pre_load


class ModelSchema(_ModelSchema):

    @pre_load
    def drop_empty_fields(self, obj):
        for x in self.Meta.drop_empty_fields:
            if x in obj and not obj[x]:
                obj.pop(x)

    class Meta(_ModelSchema.Meta):
        drop_empty_fields = ()
